# <CHANGE_ME_PROJECT> — the proof memory

> <CHANGE_ME_TAGLINE>

## Two-track ambition

**Track A — Proof Kernel.** A minimal implementation of <CHANGE_ME_TYPE_THEORY>
in Rust. The kernel is the Trusted Computing Base (TCB): ~<CHANGE_ME_TCB_BUDGET> lines,
`#![forbid(unsafe_code)]`, exhaustively tested. Everything outside the kernel
is untrusted.

**Track B — LLM Proof Search.** An LLM-powered probe that searches for
proof terms, submitting candidates to the kernel for verification. The LLM
generates; the kernel decides. This separation is the **LLM firewall** — the
central architectural invariant.

## LLM firewall

The probe (LLM) may construct proof terms. The kernel (Rust, no LLM) decides
whether they are valid. No LLM output ever bypasses the kernel. No LLM
authors a verdict. This is not a policy — it is a structural invariant
enforced by the type system and the crate boundary.

## Crate structure

| Crate | Role | TCB? |
|-------|------|------|
| `<CHANGE_ME_CORE_PKG>` | Domain types: Term, Context, Level, Judgment, Error | Yes |
| `<CHANGE_ME_KERNEL_PKG>` | Type-checking rules of inference | Yes |
| `<CHANGE_ME_PROBE_PKG>` | LLM proof-search engine | No |
| `<CHANGE_ME_SYNTAX_PKG>` | Syntax parsing and pretty-printing | No |

## Phase-0 falsifiability

The project is designed to fail fast. Phase-0 success criterion: the kernel
can check a proof constructed by an LLM probe, with the kernel under
<CHANGE_ME_TCB_BUDGET> lines. If this fails, the architecture is wrong.

